<paragraph id="8B98369F77767F5A81AFA368FD80FA8A" blockId="89.[151,1045,1291,1391]" box="[151,543,1364,1391]" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77767F5A81AFA368FE90FA8A" box="[151,271,1364,1390]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="103.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[199,1392,191,1872]" captionTargetId="figure-19@103.[184,1404,181,1882]" captionTargetPageId="103" captionText="FIGURE 9. Dorsal view of males of: a) Belonuchus sp. Q, b) B. cyanipennis (holotype), c) B. godmani. Head of B. dichrous showing the temporal carina (red arrow): d) lateral view (male), e) dorsal view (male). Dorsal view of the mandibles of males of: f) B. platypterus, g) B. viridipennis. Mandibles of Belonuchus sp. Q (male): h) dorsal view, i) ventral view. Antennae of males of: j) B. godmani, k) B. cyanipennis. Scale bars = 2.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630907" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630907/files/figure.png" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Figs. 9b, k</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77767F5A8023A368FED9FA8A" box="[283,326,1364,1390]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="106.[151,250,1870,1894]" captionTargetBox="[191,1398,191,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-25@106.[165,1422,181,1846]" captionTargetPageId="106" captionText="FIGURE 12. Mesoventrite of males of: a) Belonuchus viridipennis, b) Belonuchus sp. Q, c) B. cyanipennis. Ventral view of the left femur of male anterior leg of: d) B. apiciventris, e) B. oxyporimimus, f) B. oxyporinus, g) B. tepoztecus, h) B. bidens, i) B. viridipennis. Ventral view of the left posterior leg of males of: j) B. julietitae, k) B. linuzensis (small specimen), l) B. linuzensis (large specimen), m) B. metafemoralis, n) B. oxyporimimus, o) B. oxyporinus. Red arrow: intercoxal process of the mesoventrite, blue arrow: transverse discal ridge." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630915" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630915/files/figure.png" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">12c</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77767F5A806AA368FEE1FA8B" box="[338,382,1364,1391]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="109.[151,250,1821,1845]" captionTargetBox="[175,1417,182,1784]" captionTargetId="figure-19@109.[160,1427,181,1797]" captionTargetPageId="109" captionText="FIGURE 15. Male pregenital sternite of: a) Belonuchus alternans, b) B. oxyporinus, c) B. tepoztecus, d) B. jalappensis, e) B. iridescens, f) B. platypterus, g) B. cyanipennis, h) B. apiciventris, i) B. linuzensis, j) B. metafemoralis, k) B. rufisternus, l) B. tenuistylus, m) B. bidens, n) B. pollens, o) B. longitarsus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630921" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630921/files/figure.png" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">
<quantity id="4CDF9B7A77767F5A806AA368FEE1FA8B" box="[338,382,1364,1391]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="1.5" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" unit="g" value="15.0">15g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77767F5A80B2A368FE28FA8A" box="[394,439,1364,1390]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="114.[151,250,1910,1934]" captionTargetBox="[172,1414,182,1881]" captionTargetId="figure-25@114.[170,1417,181,1886]" captionTargetPageId="114" captionText="FIGURE 20. Male genital sternite of: a) Belonuchus cifuentesi, b) B. dichrous, c) B. flavipennis, d) B. aenigmaticus, e) B. iridescens, f) B. nigerrimus, g) B. optatus, h) B. platypterus, i) B. juanmorronei, j) B. abnormalis, k) B. pectinipes, l) B. viridipennis, m) Belonuchus sp. Q, n) B. cyanipennis, o) B. godmani. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630929/files/figure.png" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">20n</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77767F5A80FAA368FE76FA8B" box="[450,489,1364,1391]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="119.[151,250,1202,1226]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,186,1174]" captionTargetId="figure-19@119.[151,1436,181,1178]" captionTargetPageId="119" captionText="FIGURE 25. Ventral (left) and lateral (right) view of the aedeagus of: a) Belonuchus juanmorronei, b) B. abnormalis, c) B. pectinipes, d) B. viridipennis, e) Belonuchus sp. Q, f) B. cyanipennis, g) B. godmani. Scale bar = 0.5 mm (all figures)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630943" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630943/files/figure.png" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">25f</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77767F5A80CDA368FD80FA8A" box="[501,543,1364,1390]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="123.[151,250,1780,1804]" captionTargetBox="[164,1422,195,1747]" captionTargetId="figure-19@123.[151,1436,181,1756]" captionTargetPageId="123" captionText="FIGURE 29. Geographical distribution in Mexico of: a) B. linuzensis and Belonuchus sp. Q; b) B. cyanipennis, B. flavipennis and B. tepoztecus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630951" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630951/files/figure.png" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">29b</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98369F77767F5A81AFA3A0FEAFFA3E" blockId="89.[151,1437,1436,2039]" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">
Total body length 
<quantity id="4CDF9B7A77767F5A805BA3A0FE23FA53" box="[355,444,1436,1463]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.6" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" unit="mm" value="7.6">7.6 mm</quantity>
. Body black, shiny, except elytra that are metallic blue, legs dark-brown and genital segment reddish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98369F77767F5A81FFA3D8FDC3F8A6" blockId="89.[151,1437,1436,2039]" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77767F5A81FFA3D8FE98FA1A" bold="true" box="[199,263,1508,1534]" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Head</emphasis>
: oval (
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77767F5A806CA3D8FE29FA1B" box="[340,438,1508,1535]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="104.[151,250,1839,1863]" captionTargetBox="[176,1418,194,1806]" captionTargetId="figure-25@104.[152,1435,181,1816]" captionTargetPageId="104" captionText="FIGURE 10. Dorsal view of the head of males of: a) Belonuchus julietitae, b) B. singularis, c) B. connexus, d) B. platypterus, e) B. bidens, f) B. nigerrimus, g) B. optatus, h) B. cyanipennis, i) B. godmani. Dorsal view of the head and pronotum of the holotype female of: j) B. optatus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630909" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630909/files/figure.png" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Fig. 10h</figureCitation>
); ratio length/width 1.03. Dorsal surface with sulcate longitudinal midline visible in anterior half of head; punctures slightly sparser than in majority of species; front moderately foveate between antennal insertions. Eyes slightly more than 0.5 times the cephalic lateral length, notably protruding at sides. First antennomere shorter than 2–3 combined (0.75 times), antennomere 2 slightly shorter than 3 (0.8 times), antennomere 3 the smallest and oblong, 4 as long as wide, 5–10 transverse; antennomeres 4–10 of characteristic shape, like pieces of a rosary (
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77767F5A81D5A0A4FEDEF957" box="[237,321,1688,1715]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="103.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[199,1392,191,1872]" captionTargetId="figure-19@103.[184,1404,181,1882]" captionTargetPageId="103" captionText="FIGURE 9. Dorsal view of males of: a) Belonuchus sp. Q, b) B. cyanipennis (holotype), c) B. godmani. Head of B. dichrous showing the temporal carina (red arrow): d) lateral view (male), e) dorsal view (male). Dorsal view of the mandibles of males of: f) B. platypterus, g) B. viridipennis. Mandibles of Belonuchus sp. Q (male): h) dorsal view, i) ventral view. Antennae of males of: j) B. godmani, k) B. cyanipennis. Scale bars = 2.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630907" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630907/files/figure.png" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Fig. 9k</figureCitation>
). Mandibles shorter than head (ratio 0.78); narrow at base, each with a small middle tooth, no basal tooth discernible; mandibular channel slightly developed, with external margin not carinate and internal margin like impressed line extending forward slightly beyond level of middle tooth. Apical palpomere of maxillary palpi 1.8 times longer than preapical palpomere; apical palpomere of labial palpi almost as long as preapical palpomere. Head almost as wide as pronotum (ratio 1.03).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98369F77767F5981FFA170FBDDFEF9" blockId="89.[151,1437,1436,2039]" lastBlockId="90.[151,1437,151,1725]" lastPageId="90" lastPageNumber="91" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77767F5A81FFA170FEBFF882" bold="true" box="[199,288,1868,1894]" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Thorax</emphasis>
: each dorsal row of pronotum with five punctures; pronotum slightly longer than wide (ratio 1.1) and almost as wide at anterior corners as at posterior corners (ratio 1.03). Scutellum very large, nearly 1/4 of elytral length measured at center, with punctures wider and denser than on elytra, latter with fine and sparse punctation. Prosternum with a narrow transverse area near anterior margin delimited backwards by slightly visible impressed line. Intercoxal process of mesoventrite (
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77767F5A8356A1E0FD51F812" box="[622,718,2012,2038]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="106.[151,250,1870,1894]" captionTargetBox="[191,1398,191,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-25@106.[165,1422,181,1846]" captionTargetPageId="106" captionText="FIGURE 12. Mesoventrite of males of: a) Belonuchus viridipennis, b) Belonuchus sp. Q, c) B. cyanipennis. Ventral view of the left femur of male anterior leg of: d) B. apiciventris, e) B. oxyporimimus, f) B. oxyporinus, g) B. tepoztecus, h) B. bidens, i) B. viridipennis. Ventral view of the left posterior leg of males of: j) B. julietitae, k) B. linuzensis (small specimen), l) B. linuzensis (large specimen), m) B. metafemoralis, n) B. oxyporimimus, o) B. oxyporinus. Red arrow: intercoxal process of the mesoventrite, blue arrow: transverse discal ridge." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630915" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630915/files/figure.png" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Fig. 12c</figureCitation>
) triangularly scutellum-shaped, but with its apex not as acute; transverse discal ridge well developed like curved wave, laterally reaching very close to margin of intercoxal process. Legs long and slender, with few setae and spines, particularly hind legs. Profemur without row of spines at external margin, internal margin visible only near apex of femur where having three to four small spines. Metafemur without modifications or spines. Tarsomeres very slender and not flattened dorsally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98369F77757F5981FFA71AFAE5FDD9" blockId="90.[151,1437,151,1725]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77757F5981FFA71AFEA3FEA4" bold="true" box="[199,316,294,320]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Abdomen</emphasis>
: punctures and setae at medial part of each tergite very sparse, majority of setae large and placed at all margins of each tergite, so dorsal part of abdomen looks very glossy. Visible tergites 1–3 with fine posterior basal transverse carina, adjacent area weakly depressed, on tergite 3 practically not visible. Visible sternites 1–3 with entire surface covered with dense, wide-superficial punctures, combined with fine punctures, its density decreasing from anterior to posterior margin and from first visible to fifth visible sternite, on sixth visible sternite only with fine punctures. Male pregenital sternite not emarginate at posterior margin (
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77757F59828CA7E7FB89FE11" box="[948,1046,474,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="109.[151,250,1821,1845]" captionTargetBox="[175,1417,182,1784]" captionTargetId="figure-19@109.[160,1427,181,1797]" captionTargetPageId="109" captionText="FIGURE 15. Male pregenital sternite of: a) Belonuchus alternans, b) B. oxyporinus, c) B. tepoztecus, d) B. jalappensis, e) B. iridescens, f) B. platypterus, g) B. cyanipennis, h) B. apiciventris, i) B. linuzensis, j) B. metafemoralis, k) B. rufisternus, l) B. tenuistylus, m) B. bidens, n) B. pollens, o) B. longitarsus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630921" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630921/files/figure.png" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">
Fig. 
<quantity id="4CDF9B7A77757F5982D1A7E6FB89FE11" box="[1001,1046,474,501]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="1.5" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" unit="g" value="15.0">15g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
). Genital segment yellowish. Male genital sternite very elongate (3.14 times longer than wide), moderately asymmetrical, anterior portion occupying 36% and posterior portion 64% of its length, apical emargination very deep (
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77757F5982CAA41FFBCAFDD9" box="[1010,1109,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="114.[151,250,1910,1934]" captionTargetBox="[172,1414,182,1881]" captionTargetId="figure-25@114.[170,1417,181,1886]" captionTargetPageId="114" captionText="FIGURE 20. Male genital sternite of: a) Belonuchus cifuentesi, b) B. dichrous, c) B. flavipennis, d) B. aenigmaticus, e) B. iridescens, f) B. nigerrimus, g) B. optatus, h) B. platypterus, i) B. juanmorronei, j) B. abnormalis, k) B. pectinipes, l) B. viridipennis, m) Belonuchus sp. Q, n) B. cyanipennis, o) B. godmani. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630929/files/figure.png" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Fig. 20n</figureCitation>
). Abdominal styli slender.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98369F77757F5981FFA47AFD78FD61" blockId="90.[151,1437,151,1725]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77757F5981FFA47AFEA5FD84" bold="true" box="[199,314,582,608]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Aedeagus</emphasis>
: length 1.0 mm; oval in basal half and subparallel in apical half; apex subacute; basal half wider than apical half; internal sac weakly developed (
<figureCitation id="131C2A1A77757F598345A457FD44FD61" box="[637,731,618,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="119.[151,250,1202,1226]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,186,1174]" captionTargetId="figure-19@119.[151,1436,181,1178]" captionTargetPageId="119" captionText="FIGURE 25. Ventral (left) and lateral (right) view of the aedeagus of: a) Belonuchus juanmorronei, b) B. abnormalis, c) B. pectinipes, d) B. viridipennis, e) Belonuchus sp. Q, f) B. cyanipennis, g) B. godmani. Scale bar = 0.5 mm (all figures)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6630943" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6630943/files/figure.png" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Fig. 25f</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98369F77757F5981FFA4B2FD52FC09" blockId="90.[151,1437,151,1725]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77757F5981FFA4B2FED8FD4C" bold="true" box="[199,327,654,680]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Variability</emphasis>
. Total body length in males 
<quantity id="4CDF9B7A77757F5983BAA4B2FD7AFD4D" box="[642,741,654,681]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.35" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" unit="mm" value="7.35">7.35 mm</quantity>
(range 
<quantity id="4CDF9B7A77757F598201A4B3FC5CFD4D" box="[825,963,655,681]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.199999999999999" metricValueMax="8.1" metricValueMin="6.3" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" unit="mm" value="7.199999999999999" valueMax="8.1" valueMin="6.3">6.3–8.1 mm</quantity>
), in females 
<quantity id="4CDF9B7A77757F598576A4B3FB2DFD4D" box="[1102,1202,655,681]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.41" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" unit="mm" value="7.41">7.41 mm</quantity>
(range 
<quantity id="4CDF9B7A77757F59843DA4B3FA0FFD4D" box="[1285,1424,655,681]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.3999999999999995" metricValueMax="8.2" metricValueMin="6.6" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" unit="mm" value="7.3999999999999995" valueMax="8.2" valueMin="6.6">6.6–8.2 mm</quantity>
); ratio length/width of head in males 0.93 (range 0.90–0.95), in females 0.94 (range 0.91–0.95); ratio mandibular length/cephalic length in males 0.73 (range 0.60–0.85), in females 0.72 (range 0.70–0.75); ratio cephalic width/pronotal width in males 1.12 (range 1.07–1.16), in females 1.10 (range 1.05–1.16); ratio length/width of pronotum in males 1.13 (range 1.09–1.17), in females 1.15 (range 1.10–1.21); ratio anterior width/posterior width of pronotum in males 1.05 (range 1.03–1.08), in females 1.04 (range 1.00–1.08). Furthermore, the dorsal surface of head is more convex in some specimens; the metallic hue of elytra is mainly bluish, but may be slightly greenish or more rarely purplish violet; anterior portion of prosternum may not show the impressed line that separates it from the rest of prosternum; wide-superficial punctures can be dense on first visible sternite, less dense on second sternite, sparse on third sternite and very sparse on fourth sternite.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98369F77757F5981FFA5CAFF48FBBD" blockId="90.[151,1437,151,1725]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77757F5981FFA5CAFE53FBF5" bold="true" box="[199,460,1014,1041]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Taxonomic comments</emphasis>
. The main differences to distinguish 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D1C77757F59824DA5CBFB83FBF4" authorityName="Márquez &amp; Asiain" authorityYear="2022" box="[885,1052,1015,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Belonuchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyanipennis">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77757F59824DA5CBFB83FBF4" box="[885,1052,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">B. cyanipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="4C274D1C77757F59855BA5CBFB7AFBF5" baseAuthorityName="Sharp" baseAuthorityYear="1885" box="[1123,1253,1015,1041]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Belonuchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="godmani">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77757F59855BA5CBFB7AFBF5" box="[1123,1253,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">B. godmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the same as those included in the key and since there are only two species in this group, it is not considered necessary to repeat them.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33D651477757F5981FFA25FFBA0FB45" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B98369F77757F5981FFA25FFBA0FB45" blockId="90.[151,1437,151,1725]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">
<emphasis id="B953EA8D77757F5981FFA25FFED7FB99" bold="true" box="[199,328,1123,1149]" pageId="90" pageNumber="91">Etymology</emphasis>
. The name of this species is a combination of the words “cyaneus” and “pennis”, which denotes the dark blue metallic coloration of its elytra, while the rest of the body is glossy black.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
